# OSS Contributor Playbook for Dr. Siddharth Rajasekar

**Goal:** Become a recognized contributor/maintainer in the open-source healthcare + AI ecosystem.
**Edge:** MBBS-qualified doctor with deep operational expertise in healthcare authority systems, behavioral science, NMC compliance, and content strategy for physicians.
**Timeline:** 3–6 months to meaningful contributor status; 6–12 months to maintainer consideration.

---

## Your Contribution Lane

You are not competing with engineers on code. You are contributing what engineers literally cannot: clinical domain expertise, medical regulatory knowledge, and real-world healthcare operational frameworks.

Your contributions will fall into these categories:

1. **Clinical accuracy reviews** — Flagging medically incorrect or misleading content in healthcare AI repos
2. **Regulatory compliance frameworks** — NMC, GMC, AHPRA, HIPAA compliance checklists and guidelines that developers need but can't write
3. **Healthcare domain content** — Templates, scoring rubrics, patient journey maps, and operational SOPs that make healthcare tools actually useful
4. **Documentation with clinical context** — Turning engineer-written docs into something healthcare professionals can actually use
5. **Curated resource additions** — Adding high-quality, clinically validated resources to awesome-lists

---

## Tier 1: Start Here (Week 1–4)

These repos are the easiest entry point. Low barrier, high visibility, and your domain expertise is immediately valuable.

### 1. awesome-healthcare (kakoni/awesome-healthcare)

**What it is:** The most popular curated list of open-source healthcare software, tools, and resources. 3k+ stars.

**Why you:** You know the healthcare software landscape from a practitioner's perspective. Most contributors are developers adding tools they built. A doctor adding clinically-relevant resources with context on why they matter is rare and valuable.

**First 3 moves:**

- **PR #1:** Add 3–5 missing healthcare tools you actually use or know are valuable (must be open-source). Follow their format exactly: `[Tool Name](link) - One line description.` Read their CONTRIBUTING.md first.
- **PR #2:** Suggest a new category or sub-section that's missing — e.g., "Patient Communication Tools" or "Medical Compliance & Regulatory" if not already present.
- **PR #3:** Open an issue proposing clinical validation labels — a way to tag which tools have been reviewed/endorsed by healthcare professionals.

**Repo link:** https://github.com/kakoni/awesome-healthcare
**Contributing guide:** https://github.com/kakoni/awesome-healthcare/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md

---

### 2. awesome-healthcare-ai (medtorch/awesome-healthcare-ai)

**What it is:** Curated list of healthcare AI tools, algorithms, datasets, and research papers. Organized by medical specialty.

**Why you — this is your golden ticket:** The maintainer explicitly states they are NOT a medical specialist and there may be mistakes. They need exactly what you are — a doctor who can validate, correct, and expand the clinical content.

**First 3 moves:**

- **PR #1:** Review and improve the content in 2–3 specialty areas you know well (IVF/reproductive medicine, dermatology, dental, orthopedics). Fix any clinical inaccuracies. Add missing landmark papers or tools.
- **PR #2:** Add a new specialty section for a field that's missing or underrepresented, with curated resources you can vouch for clinically.
- **PR #3:** Open an issue offering to serve as a clinical reviewer for the repo. Frame it: "I'm an MBBS-qualified doctor. I can validate clinical accuracy across specialty sections. Happy to do ongoing reviews."

**Repo link:** https://github.com/medtorch/awesome-healthcare-ai

