## Tier 2: Deeper Engagement (Week 4–12)

Once you have a few merged PRs and visible activity, move to repos where sustained contribution leads to maintainer-track recognition.

### 4. OpenClaw-Medical-Skills (FreedomIntelligence)

**What it is:** The largest open-source medical AI skills library — 869 skills covering biomedical and clinical research. Each skill is a SKILL.md file that teaches an AI agent specialized domain knowledge.

**Why you:** You already build SKILL.md files (your Brand Doctor and HAOS systems are essentially skill architectures). You understand how to structure clinical knowledge for AI consumption. Most contributors are engineers writing skills about tools they understand technically but not clinically.

**How to contribute:**

- **Review existing skills** in your specialty areas for clinical accuracy. Open issues for any that have medical errors or misleading guidance.
- **Write new skills** in areas you know deeply — e.g., "NMC Compliance Checker for Medical Content," "Patient Authority Assessment," "Healthcare Brand Audit Framework."
- **Propose a healthcare compliance skill category** if it doesn't exist — regulatory compliance across jurisdictions (India NMC, UK GMC, US state medical boards).

**Repo link:** https://github.com/FreedomIntelligence/OpenClaw-Medical-Skills

---

### 5. Isaree-Platform (Isaree-ai)

**What it is:** Open-source, medical-compliant AI assistant and agent orchestration engine. Built for HIPAA/GDPR compliance. In active development — not yet production-ready.

**Why you:** They explicitly welcome "healthcare professionals, researchers, and anyone interested in advancing medical AI." An early-stage project with an active team that wants clinical input. Getting in early = getting recognized as a core contributor when the project grows.

**How to contribute:**

- **Start with issues:** Review open issues and comment on anything where your clinical perspective adds value.
- **Documentation:** Improve their docs with real-world healthcare workflow context. Engineers write docs about how the code works; you can write docs about how the clinical workflow works.
- **Compliance frameworks:** Contribute NMC/Indian medical regulatory context if they're focused on HIPAA/GDPR. Expanding their compliance coverage to India/Asia is a unique, high-value contribution.

**Repo link:** https://github.com/Isaree-ai/Isaree-Platform

---

### 6. Open Hospital (informatici/openhospital)

**What it is:** Free and open-source Electronic Health Record (EHR) system, deployed in hospitals in developing countries.

**Why you:** They have a dedicated documentation repo (openhospital-doc) and welcome non-developer contributors. As an MBBS doctor, you can review clinical workflows, validate that the EHR design matches real clinical practice, and improve user-facing documentation from a practitioner's perspective.

**How to contribute:**

- **Documentation PRs** in the openhospital-doc repo — review for clinical accuracy, improve workflow descriptions
- **Open issues** identifying UX problems or clinical workflow gaps you'd notice as a practicing doctor
- **Join their Slack** and start answering clinical questions that engineers can't

**Repo link:** https://github.com/informatici/openhospital
**Docs repo:** https://github.com/informatici/openhospital-doc

